        routeDescription: "The route takes the A43 to Chambéry, then the N90 via Albertville and Moûtiers. After Aime, the climb to La Plagne is via the D220 through the villages of Macot and La Roche.",
        introduction: "La Plagne, created in 1961 as part of France's Plan Neige, has become one of the world's most visited ski resorts, welcoming over 2.5 million skier-days per season. Comprising 11 villages and sites from 1,250 to 2,100 metres altitude (Plagne Centre, Plagne Bellecôte, Plagne Villages, Belle Plagne, Plagne 1800, Aime 2000, Plagne Soleil, Montalbert, Montchavin, Les Coches and Champagny-en-Vanoise), La Plagne offers a uniquely diverse range of atmospheres. The resort's own area covers 225 km of runs for all levels, and access to the Paradiski domain via the Vanoise Express brings the total to 425 km. The resort is also famous for its Olympic bobsleigh track, built for the 1992 Albertville Olympics and open to the public for bob-raft descents. The taxi transfer from Lyon is ideal for large families who appreciate door-to-door service without managing rail connections and children's equipment. TaxiNeo offers spacious vehicles with child seats on request.",
        itineraire: "The route takes the A43 from Lyon towards Chambéry, then the N90 through the Tarentaise valley to Aime (830 m). From Aime, the driver takes the D220 climbing to La Plagne through the villages of Macot-la-Plagne and La Roche. The road winds through spruce forest before emerging onto the La Plagne plateau, a vast open space at 1,800-2,100 m. Depending on your accommodation, the driver takes you to Plagne Centre, Belle Plagne, Plagne Bellecôte or any other resort site. For villages on the opposite side (Montchavin, Les Coches, Champagny-en-Vanoise), an alternative route from Moûtiers or Bozel may be used. The final climb offers spectacular panoramas of the Tarentaise valley and Mont Pourri (3,779 m) in the background. Tolls included in the fare: approximately €20.",
